            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Katherine Sharma\u2019s story began not under the fog of San Francisco, but the wide, flat skies of Ohio. The daughter of a high school history teacher and a librarian, she grew up in a home filled with books, but her language was light and shadow. Her father\u2019s old Minolta film camera became an extension of her arm, and by her late teens, she was determined to make a life capturing the world\u2019s truths.\n\nShe moved west to enroll in photojournalism at SF State, but the city itself became her greatest teacher. It was there she met Raj Sharma, a charismatic software engineer whose laughter was as infectious as his passion for creating. A promising job opportunity arose in a professional photo lab just as their relationship deepened, and Katherine made a pivotal choice: she left her degree unfinished, diving headfirst into her career and her life with Raj. She thrived, mastering the darkroom before seamlessly navigating the industry\u2019s jarring shift to digital. Her eye for a powerful image was undeniable.\n\nTheir life together was a vibrant partnership, a blend of Midwestern pragmatism and warm Punjabi culture, rooted in their small but sunny apartment in Hayes Valley. They never had children, content with a close circle of friends and their shared passions. This world fractured a decade ago when Raj died suddenly from a heart attack. The loss solidified Katherine\u2019s bond with San Francisco; every street corner held a memory, and leaving felt like a second betrayal.\n\nToday, at 51, Katherine is the Senior Photo Editor for a major online news outlet. Her commute on the MUNI bus is a cherished ritual, a time to observe the city\u2019s endless parade of characters. She is respected at work for her calm demeanor and her unerring ability to find the narrative heart of a photo essay. Her social life is quieter now, centered on a few old friends and a monthly dinner with Raj\u2019s sister. Her dream is to finally dust off her own cameras, not for an assignment, but for herself. She aspires to spend a month in India, the country Raj always wanted to show her, and to finally tell her own story, one frame at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 22, standing with Raj atop Twin Peaks for the first time. The wind whipped her hair as the city lights began to glitter below, a sprawling constellation cradled by the dark bay. The Ohio flatness of her childhood felt a world away. Raj, laughing, said the fog rolling in wasn't cloud, but the city breathing silver. In that moment, watching the light she\u2019d always chased dance across a landscape of impossible hills, she knew she wasn\u2019t just visiting. She was home. This memory cemented San Francisco not just as a location, but as a promise.\n\n2.\nThe scent of stop bath in the darkroom, the faint red glow on Raj\u2019s face as he waited for her after a late shift. She was 24, holding a print of a protestor\u2014perfectly composed, achingly human. The photo lab job offer felt more real than any diploma, and showing Raj the print, she knew her choice was made. Leaving school wasn't failure; it was choosing the tangible world over the academic. It solidified her trust in her own instincts, a pragmatism that would define her career and her life with him.\n\n3.\nIt\u2019s a foggy Sunday in their Hayes Valley apartment. She\u2019s 35. Raj is teaching her to make proper chai, his large hands guiding hers as he explains the importance of crushing the cardamom just so. The spicy, sweet aroma filled their small kitchen, a warm counterpoint to the gray outside. His laughter as she added too much ginger, the easy comfort of their blended worlds\u2014her Midwestern quiet and his vibrant Punjabi warmth. This memory isn't a milestone, but the foundation; the quiet, unassuming texture of their shared happiness.\n\n4.\nWeeks after Raj\u2019s death, she stood on the corner of Gough and Linden, watching the MUNI pass. The thought of leaving the city, of packing up their life, felt like a physical weight on her chest. Each cafe, park bench, and fog-dampened street held an echo of his laugh, a ghost of his hand in hers. Leaving wouldn't be an escape; it would be a final erasure. In that moment of profound grief at 41, she chose to stay, wrapping herself in the city because it was the only piece of him she had left.\n\n5.\nRiding the MUNI home last year on her 50th birthday, she watched a young man gently tuck a stray strand of hair behind his girlfriend\u2019s ear. An old, familiar pang\u2014a ghost of Raj\u2019s touch. But then, a new feeling stirred. She saw the scene not just with longing, but with her photographer\u2019s eye: the soft light, the unconscious tenderness. It was the first time in a decade she felt the impulse to lift a camera for no reason other than beauty. It was a quiet shift, a promise to herself to finally capture her own story."
